subSubSection.paragraph:
Note: There has been no record of
A. coreana
from China for a long time (
Smetana, 2004 b
;
Luo & Zhao, 2012
), but it was recently added to the Chinese fauna (see
Schülke & Smetana, 2015
).

Head (
Fig. 19
): semicircular, as long as width (HW/HL = 1.16 , n = 20 ), widest at posterior part of eyes; setae on vertex rather dense but inconspicuous, directed anteriomedially; punctation medium in size, scattered rather densely; vertex longitudinally lack of punctation at middle, but small to medium in size. Eyes: medium in length, occupying approximately half length of head, slightly protruding laterally.

Antennae (
Fig. 37
): short, moderately shorter than head and pronotum combined; thick, setose, with antennomere IV moderately transverse, but antennomeres V to X strongly transverse in approximately same width each; antennomere XI symmetrical, obtusely rounded at apex; approximate relative length of antennomeres from basal to apex: 20 (including base): 9 : 11 : 4 : 4.5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 14 .

Pronotum (
Fig. 1
): transversely oval (PW/PL = 1.36 , n = 20 ), strongly narrowing anterad, moderately longer than sutural length of elytra, widest around below of basal half, basal margin weakly rounded; pubescence dense, directed laterally and posterolaterally; punctation small and shallow but covered with densely and uniformly.

Mesoventrite (
Fig. 28
): inter coxal process rather narrowly elongate, with rounded apex, completely reaching to inter coxal process of metaventrite.

Metaventrite (
Fig. 28
): inter coxal process of metaventrite small but rather obtusely pointed apically.

Elytra (
Fig. 1
): together, transverse (EW/EL = 1.99 , n = 20 ), rather small, slightly smaller than pronotum, widest at middle; fine pubescence scattered densely, diverging posteriorly on each elytron; dorsal surface rough and impressed moderately; posterolateral corners of each elytron not sinuate.

Legs (
Fig. 1
): simple, short, moderately slender; fore and midtibia, densely covered with undeveloped spines, respectively.

Abdomen (
Fig. 1
): first three visible tergites deeply impressed transversely at base; dorsal and ventral surface moderately covered with thin and long setae.

Male : tergite VIII (
Fig. 45
): posterior margin smooth, not serrate at all, broadly shallowly emarginate medially; dorsal surface covered with setae rather densely, with approximately 11 macrosetae. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 47
): posterior margin broadly rounded, with a row of minute sensory setae densely (see
Yamamoto & Maruyama, 2012
: 10 ), and with a complex-cluster of very minute setae just behind the row of minute setae; ventral surface covered with setae densely, with approximately 12 macrosetae. Median lobe of aedeagus (
Figs 49–50
): [lateral view (
Fig. 49
)]: robust, gradually narrowing apically; apical lobe pointed, not hook-shaped at apex; [parameral view (
Fig. 50
)]: bulbous, with basal part widely rounded; apical lobe abruptly narrowing moderately near apex, with thin and sharply pointed apex; a series of complex sclerites, reaching to almost basal margin of median lobe.

Female : tergite VIII (
Fig. 51
): posterior margin as in male; dorsal surface covered with setae densely, with approximately 11 macrosetae. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 48
): posterior margin very weakly rounded broadly or almost truncate; ventral surface covered with setae densely, with approximately 13 macrosetae; no complex-cluster of minute setae situated near posterior margin. Spermatheca (
Fig. 51
): C-shaped; apical invagination of spermatheca very small, inconspicuous, shallowly inward; spermathecal head and neck weakly elliptical shape together; attachment of spermathecal duct inconspicuous; basal part of spermathecal stem widely curved, much longer than spermathecal head and neck combined; chitinized portion of spermathecal stem moderately long, as long as spermathecal head and neck combined; each part of spermatheca uniformly and weakly sclerotized; inner wall of spermathecal head and neck coarsely striate, that of basal part not reticulate at all.
